Yeah, I feel this. I was told that I was intimidating more than once. For example when a shy boy was eating with me and a friend because he was staying at our house overnight. He finished his food but didn't stand up. Turns out he's been waiting for me to give him my permission to leave the room and go upstairs. To me, that was so respecful and I felt very much valued and equal. He respected me as something close to his host even though I was not the man owning the house. But everyone else is turning this into a bad thing. They tell me that I might have been too straight forward or even too bossy so I cared him off. But that's straight up who I am: open, talkative, lively... How can u turn that into a bad thing and try to make me feel bad about this just because I am a woman. Because seemingly only men are allowed to give permissions or receive f*cking respect.
With men it's considered to be very natural and manly to have a very active personality and like to take the lead during conversations. But as soon as a woman takes on a little bit of a "leader role" and stands up for her believes it's considered intimidating and hella bossy. What is wrong with this society?! Stop with your double standards!

snippet.textDisplay:
When my brother was 15 and had a girlfriend, he and my dad would "high five".
At 15, I was not even allowed to have a boyfriend.

My dad absolutely had a different set of rules for each of us and it wasnt right because it was all based on the fact that I wasn't a boy.

Dont get be wrong, I was Daddy's girl and always felt loved but my brother was his "boy" and we didnt have the same experience as children.

The double standard is there even in families that don't recognize it because its been so engrained in our society.

My dad wasnt even aware that he was doing this because my brother and I are 5 years apart and he forgot about the rules that my brother never had.

Hopefully, in the next generation this double standard will no longer exist because we know better now.
